PhoenixDKIM 3.0.0-beta14 release notes
=======================================

Date: 28 May 2026

This is a hotfix release. It fixes a single issue introduced in beta13:
when PhoenixDKIM was built without libsystemd, the shipped systemd unit
was still Type=notify, causing "systemctl start" to hang until the
timeout.


Bug fixes
---------

[Fix 20260528] Fixed a hang during "systemctl start" when PhoenixDKIM
was built without libsystemd. In beta13, WITH_SYSTEMD defaulted ON but
only gated the library search; a build without libsystemd silently
produced a binary without sd_notify support, yet the shipped unit was
still Type=notify — so systemd waited for a READY=1 signal that the
daemon could never send.

The fix makes the dependency honest end to end:

  - WITH_SYSTEMD is now a tri-state option: AUTO (default, detects
    and warns if absent), ON (requires libsystemd — configure fails
    if it is missing), or OFF (disables sd_notify entirely).

  - The -V "Configured with" line now reports systemd based on what
    was actually compiled (HAVE_LIBSYSTEMD), not the request value.

  - The systemd unit is generated from a template
    (contrib/systemd/opendkim.service.in) so its Type= and WatchdogSec
    match the build: Type=notify with watchdog when sd_notify is
    compiled in; Type=simple (no watchdog) otherwise, so the service
    still starts cleanly.

  - A new INSTALL_SYSTEMD_UNIT cmake option (default ON on Linux)
    installs the generated unit; the Debian package passes OFF to
    avoid colliding with its own packaged copy.

  - The Debian Build-Depends now includes libsystemd-dev [linux-any]
    so the package always builds with notify support.

  - The static debian/opendkim.service had a literal @sbindir@ in
    ExecStart and ExecPaths; corrected to /usr/sbin.
